# Project Rules

<!--
  Fill this in for your project. Everything in angle brackets is a placeholder
  to replace. This article describes WHAT the swarm should build and any
  project-specific rules.
-->

## Project Shape
- SwarmForge project with four agents: specifier, coder, refactorer, and architect.
- The specifier is the master worktree role; the others work in their own worktrees.
- The architect consumes handoffs in batch mode.
- Project language: <FILL IN, e.g. Python, Go, TypeScript>. Use that language's
  standard unit-test and acceptance-test runners and local verification.

## Task
- <Describe the behavior you want built. The specifier turns it into Gherkin
  acceptance specifications and asks for approval before handing off to the coder.
  Prefer starting with one feature and letting the pipeline run before adding more.>

## Tooling Note
- If a tool named in a role prompt (coverage, CRAP, DRY, mutation, ir-dry-checker)
  is not installed, note it in one line and skip it rather than installing anything.

## Local Configuration
- Keep swarm state under `.swarmforge/` and worktrees under `.worktrees/`.

## Handoffs
- Prefer terse, explicit handoffs that report state and request role-appropriate
  review. Do not include verifications or sender process narrative.

## Ownership
- Do not change another role's prompt or workflow ownership without explicit user
  direction.
